SIMPLE: wedge
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wedge
<hw>Wedge</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧j)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wegge</ets>, AS. <ets>wecg</ets>; akin to D. <ets>wig</ets>,
<ets>wigge</ets>, OHG. <ets>wecki</ets>, G. <ets>weck</ets> a
(wedge-shaped) loaf, Icel. <ets>veggr</ets>, Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧gge</ets>,
Sw. <ets>vigg</ets>, and probably to Lith. <ets>vagis</ets> a peg. Cf.
<er>Wigg</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A piece of metal, or other hard material, thick at
one end, and tapering to a thin edge at the other, used in splitting
wood, rocks, etc., in raising heavy bodies, and the like. It is one of
the six elementary machines called the <xex>mechanical powers</xex>. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <cref>Mechanical powers</cref>, under
<er>Mechanical</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A solid of five sides, having a
rectangular base, two rectangular or trapezoidal sides meeting in an
edge, and two triangular ends.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A mass of metal, especially when of a wedgelike
form.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Wedges</xex> of gold.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything in the form of a wedge, as a body of troops
drawn up in such a form.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In warlike muster they appear,⟦br⟧
In rhombs, and <qex>wedges</qex>, and half-moons, and wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The person whose name stands lowest on the list of
the classical tripos; -- so called after a person (<xex>Wedge</xex>wood)
who occupied this position on the first list of 1828.</def> <mark>[Cant,
Cambridge Univ., Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>C. A. Bristed.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>A <isa>golf club</isa> having an
iron head with the face nearly horizontal, used for lofting the golf
ball at a high angle, as when hitting the ball out of a sand trap or the
rough.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fox wedge</b></col>. <fld>(Mach. & Carpentry)</fld>
<cd>See under <er>Fox</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Spherical wedge</b></col>
<fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the portion of a sphere included between two
planes which intersect in a diameter.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wedge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wedge
<hw>Wedge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wedged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wedging</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cleave or separate with a wedge or wedges, or as
with a wedge; to rive.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My heart, as <xex>wedged</xex> with
a sigh, would rive in twain.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To force or drive as a wedge is driven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Among the crowd in the abbey where a finger⟦br⟧
Could not be <qex>wedged</qex> in more.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He 's just the sort of man to <qex>wedge</qex> himself into a snug
berth.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs. J. H. Ewing.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To force by crowding and pushing as a wedge does;
<as>as, to <ex>wedge</ex> one's way</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To press closely; to fix, or make fast, in the
manner of a wedge that is driven into something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wedged</qex> in the rocky shoals, and sticking fast.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fasten with a wedge, or with wedges; <as>as, to
<ex>wedge</ex> a scythe on the snath; to <ex>wedge</ex> a rail or a
piece of timber in its place</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Pottery)</fld> <def>To cut, as clay, into wedgelike
masses, and work by dashing together, in order to expel air bubbles,
etc.</def> <rj><au>Tomlinson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wedgebill</ent>⟦br⟧
